<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Inline Assessment MathML 1.4//EN" "http://oli.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_inline_assessment_mathml_1_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="lymph_CMIR_lbd2"><title>tutor</title><page><question id="q1"><body><p>Complete the following paragraph:</p><p>Antibody-mediated immunity works mainly against <input_ref input="one" /> pathogens, which include any bacteria, fungi or viruses that are in the extracellular fluids of the body. B cells respond to unprocessed antigens, but their response is more intense if they process the antigen and receive costimulation by <input_ref input="two" /> T cells. Once activated, B cells produce clones of <input_ref input="three" /> cells and memory cells which reside in lymphatic tissues (such as MALT, lymph nodes and spleen). Plasma cells produce <input_ref input="four" />, which leave the lymphatic tissue and circulate in body fluids. Antibodies can be grouped into <input_ref input="five" /> classes each with specific biological roles. Actions of antibodies include neutralization, immobilization, agglutination and precipitation of antigen. In addition, antibodies can activate <input_ref input="six" /> and enhance phagocytosis.</p></body><fill_in_the_blank id="one" shuffle="true"><choice value="a">intracellular</choice><choice value="b">extracellular</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank id="two" shuffle="true"><choice value="a">helper</choice><choice value="b">cytotoxic</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank id="three" shuffle="true"><choice value="a">naïve</choice><choice value="b">plasma</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank id="four" shuffle="true"><choice value="a">cytokines</choice><choice value="b">antibodies</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank id="five" shuffle="true"><choice value="a">four</choice><choice value="b">five</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank id="six" shuffle="true"><choice value="a">complement</choice><choice value="b">histamine</choice></fill_in_the_blank><part id="one"><skillref idref="lymph_CMIR2_SKILL" /><response input="one" match="a" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect.</feedback></response><response input="one" match="b" score="1"><feedback>Correct.</feedback></response><hint>B cells can respond to unprocessed antigens.</hint></part><part id="two"><skillref idref="lymph_CMIR2_SKILL" /><response input="two" match="a" score="1"><feedback>Correct.</feedback></response><response input="two" match="b" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect.</feedback></response><hint>Costimulation is the cytokine IL-2.</hint></part><part id="three"><skillref idref="lymph_CMIR2_SKILL" /><response input="three" match="a" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect</feedback></response><response input="three" match="b" score="1"><feedback>Correct.</feedback></response><hint>Naïve cells are cells that have not yet encountered a pathogen.</hint></part><part id="four"><skillref idref="lymph_CMIR2_SKILL" /><response input="four" match="a" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect.</feedback></response><response input="four" match="b" score="1"><feedback>Correct.</feedback></response><hint>Cytokines are chemical signals.</hint></part><part id="five"><skillref idref="lymph_CMIR2_SKILL" /><response input="five" match="a" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect.</feedback></response><response input="five" match="b" score="1"><feedback>Correct.</feedback></response><hint>The function of IgD is not as well understood as the other isotypes of antibodies.</hint></part><part id="six"><skillref idref="lymph_CMIR2_SKILL" /><response input="six" match="a" score="1"><feedback>Correct.</feedback></response><response input="six" match="b" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect.</feedback></response><hint>Histamine is released from mast cells and basophils.</hint></part></question></page></assessment>
